segments.text: Okay, Jim, Billingsley, let's see, today is May the 9th, I think.
Saturday is the 10th.
I've got a calendar here.
Saturday is the 10th, May the 10th, 1997.
Welcome to Jim Billingsley.
And Jim, tell me your full name, please.
Jimmy.
Jimmy, is it right?
Right, J-I-M-M-Y.
That's your regular official name, okay.
That is correct.
Middle initial or name?
L-I-L. L-I-S-L-E or L-Y?
L-Y-S-L-E. L-Y-S-L-E. And where were you born?
And what year?
May I ask?
Okay.
We're almost contemporaries.
The Social Security Office has a different opinion of the day that I was born in July.
Okay.
All my life I thought it was the 26th, but when I applied for Social Security they told me it was the 27th.
Is that right?
That's interesting.
So, thank you.
Okay.
Within 24 hours.
And you're...
Your parents were doing what in Fulton?
Uh, he had been brought there some years before it was managed.
Telephone office.
With what telephone?
Local?
Southwest.
Southwest Middletown.
And, uh, that was in Gene Autry's time.
And, uh, I don't know exactly when, but they moved there about that.
And Gene Autry was a telegrapher?
He was a telegrapher, uh-huh.
With the, uh, with the Tahoe gun there, or with the railroad?
Uh, I think the railroad.
Yeah, I think so, because I had an uncle who was a telegrapher, and I remember that.
I'm going to put that in the book, and I think that's... Also, there was another guy, an interesting
now that he was there about that time.
He may have even been the owner of P.J.
Cochran, C-O-N-K-W-R-I-G-H-T, who later became the chief designer at the Oklahoma Chris.
And later after that went to Princeton as their chief designer.
But he was out of retirement then.
He shared, I'm told, a studio with Redwood Gowdy, the Redwood Old Titans fan, in Chicago.
That's the story.
Yeah, Gowder, Gowder.
Gowdy, G-O-W-D-Y.
Okay, I've seen it, yeah.
Yeah.
And how long were you in Sepulchre?
Until 1935, and was transferred to Tulsa.
So then you grew up in Tulsa?
Yeah, actually grew up in Tulsa.
And did you go through high school and the whole business in Tulsa?
Yeah, kindergarten through high school.
And?
And beyond that, actually, university.
Wait, let me get this right.
So you left
After high school.
Went to OSU.
Went to OSU, okay.
And then in service, and then came back to TU, and I finished there in 58.
At Texas?
No, Tulsa.
At Tulsa, yeah.
And you finished at Tulsa in 58?
What were you in the service?
In the Navy?
No, I was in the Army.
One of the only atomic artillery units.
What was that?
280 millimeter field piece.
It's the one that they fired the warhead, atomic warhead, down the corridor.
It was a life magazine.
You may remember the old picture.
I think I may remember.
It's got a gun in the foreground, and a 11-inch gun.
And we never would get to Korea.
That's interesting.
Korea.
Yeah, we're good.
They signed the name on the gun before we...
They shipped and they converted us to come to Mexico after that.
Yes, I agree.
Where'd you go in Germany?
I lived in a town called Frankfurt.
I don't know where it was.
It was in the French sector.
Not far from here.
I don't know what properties got robbed.
And out of work.
But it was in the French sector.
There was no German post in there.
The Catholic post, they lived in the old German caserns.
They used the old stone masonry facility for the Germans to build before World War I.
No one was in Germany, was there?
I think there were some of them, but... Heidelberg.
Heidelberg.
Yes, he was in Heidelberg.
I think he was in Heidelberg.
I think I've forgotten the wrong one.
I've interviewed him just recently, but I can't remember what it is.
But I do remember Heidelberg, and he was there three years, which was a good stint, as I recall.
Well, I tell you, when I was in as a recruiter, he was still trying to get us all to be more than short-timers.
Yeah.
And they tried to get me, but I went through the pattern test and all that, and brought back your CES, and then I found out it was at least a four-year stay.
And I told them, no, thank you.
I had just gotten married, and I had a baby.
So we've just been friends for interesting days, just to show you that.
Yeah.
Yeah.
They watched the spirit here, and they went to Oklahoma City for a free industrial baseball game.
And that guy came back.
A couple of guys didn't leave the bus that day, downtown in Coliseum over there.
And I guess it was CID, one of those guys, he was one of the guys, to get the guys to miss about seven hours.
And I thought, you know, doing that stuff, I like Vietnam, you know, it's, you know, it's a protest, you know, I like that.
Those guys are just going to go.
Yeah.
Well, my dad was here in the back for years.
And so, my brother and I hadn't,
No choice.
We were in the service, so we could have planned it.
And we did.
My brother actually enlisted, but I went through all of this in my life.
And all the K-fellas were supposed to stay in there.
And it wouldn't have been bad.
No, it wouldn't have been bad.
So, when you get out of service, your service really got out early because Korea was over.
and they were trying to get to me.
They opened the window early, early late, so it was a two-year ditch.
So I actually got back about a minute to you, and I got to Cal State.
Were you still under the G.I.
Bill?
Uh-huh.
Because, see, there was a drop in there, and I missed it.
Well, of course I got an undergraduate degree, but then I was going to go back to law school when G.I.
Bill, when G.I.
Bill went out.
Yeah.
We were out of there.
They closed it off because I don't know how they calculated that.
If that had been in, I would have been a lawyer now, I'm sure.
Yeah, because I had one year of law school already.
There's hope for you yet.
I was lucky.
I was lucky by now.
Really, I tell you.
But...
There was a cut-off, yeah, I remember that.
Because there was still live combat action.
They extended that.
We could have easily ignored it.
Some of us did.
Some of them did come back and flash the flags.
We were lucky.
That's right.
And then, so you went through Tulsa, finished in what?
In 15, what kind of a degree?
Really, it was commercial art.
Reading, journalism, drawing.
What, was that in the Department of Art?
It was liberal arts.
And, yeah, the Department of Art within that.
It was headed by Alexander Hogue, who was a student.
It's not been gone very long.
In fact, some of these works are in the library of Austin.
It was a technical oil spreader in Wichita during World War II.
And when that was over, we started using art as a profession and then joined Tulsa.
One of the faculty, our faculty there, was a negative person.
The youth department was a negative person.
And Brad Place, a good old Texan,
was my advisor through those years.
He was just recently, maybe not so recently, he's retired, but he's still in Pelman.
And his daughter, interestingly, is Mary Kay Price, who was on
Nash.
She was one of the nurses on Nash.
Anyway, she kind of, you know, bought a star.
Anyway.
Had you kind of grown up in art?
Oh, yeah.
Did you have high school art?
No, I didn't.
I was in drafting.
I had two years of that.
Yeah, it's good stuff.
And S. L. Denverson back there at Bill Roberts High School was a buddy and got a job with George F. Kelly.
company, which is an oil field.
He was an oil field photographer.
An entrepreneur that did mapping.
Many of his motorized maps are still working now here in oil companies all over the Southwest.
And what were you doing with an oil field?
What was your job?
Grassman.
Production?
Grassman.
Post oil production maps.
from weekly, Ira Reinhart's weekly report.
It's the information source for the industry on current production.
It's a weekly report, and we would post activities all over the Southwest.
Now, as a production draftsman, you're doing the surface type?
Yeah.
This is topographic drafting.
Okay.

And I went from cycling around to... And I had this guy who did the subsurface draft, and, you know, he'd shoot those things off, and then he'd draw little squinty lines and say, here's what it's like down there.
He hoped.
He never knew.
He, George Kelly, was so frustrated with the way Texas was laid out that he established what he called the Kelly Baseline, which is a

a grid of townships and ranges in state texas and hoping that others would look up on this this means that locating things when he ran in descriptions like three cigars west of the old old stunt locating a well it left a little to be desired but he he did that and uh

The summer of 1950.
And you stayed with them then?
All through.
I stayed with them that summer, and they went to A&M, the school, for three semesters.
And then we got married, and I went into the service following August.
But I worked for the Sun and World Companies Production Division there in Tulsa.
as a math draftsman for about six months or so.

Okay, okay.

Sunrise, which is the old big company.
Yeah.
And still is basically a production brand.
That's when I graduated as an artist, and I joined D.X.
as a commercial artist, and advertised myself.
Oh, okay.
When I came out of the service, I took a battery of tests.
We were at the VA office there on campus.
I wasn't quite sure at the moment.
I had a business curriculum set up.
But I wasn't all that confident in that decision.
So I went to VA and asked them to run me through the library test.
It was about three days.
Maybe you did it.

I know which one that was.
And the profile on that came out decidedly.
Yeah, as opposed to fine arts.
So I said, fine.
I mean, we bar graphed them right now.

That's interesting.
And so I said, OK.
I thought, well, you know, I'm a parent.
I'd still like to be a champion.
That's interesting.
It was not a bad move.
Yeah.
No, it made me so much happier.
Yeah.
And that was such a purely academic world.
So there was a master to be served there.
So you were with Sunway for until when?
That's when I went to OU.
Now how did you get to own that?
I picked up an ad in the paper.
There was nothing more than that.
OU needed a designer.
There were two there at the time.
And then the editor, they called them.
One of the few presses that called them.
You were an art editor.
You were either an assistant or associate art editor.
And the art editor assignment was reserved for only special people.
Okay.
Like PJ Compton, who I mentioned before.
Yeah, right.
And so I started doing it as the assistant art editor, which was the designer and production.
in those days and the editor the press editor director press editor director was the editor-in-chief

Western Americana.

Four years?

I went to Tennessee.
Tennessee.

Money.

Lewis.

in roughly 1968.

what happened there, and I, when they were exploring, possibly the prospect of her coming, she was coming from Princeton, and that was good, and like many other outland press, universities and press like we are, in Tennessee, and were certainly, they unfortunately thought they wanted to be
